    response: "## Moby-Dick: A Unified Reading\n\nAfter tracking four interpretive threads — obsession/hubris, race/epistemology, tragic heroism, and ecology — they converge on a single, devastating argument:\n\n**Moby-Dick is about the catastrophic consequences of *monocular vision* — the insistence on seeing the world through one lens, one framework, one set of values.**\n\nEvery thread confirms this:\n\n### Obsession → Monocular vision as psychology\nAhab reduces the infinite complexity of the world to one question: \"What is the whale trying to say to me?\" This single-lens vision is what makes him magnificent and what destroys him.\n\n### Race → Monocular vision as politics\nThe Pequod has every perspective it needs to survive — Polynesian, Indigenous, African, Western — but subordinates them all to one white captain's metaphysics. The ship sinks because it *won't use its own diversity*.\n\n### Tragic hero → Monocular vision as philosophy\nAhab's tragic error isn't pride or anger — it's **hermeneutic closure**. He decides what the whale means and refuses to revise. Every classical tragic hero shares this: the refusal to update the model in the face of new evidence.\n\n### Ecology → Monocular vision as civilization\nThe whaling industry sees whales as oil. The Enlightenment sees nature as data. Both are monocular projections that treat a complex system as a single resource. The system eventually fights back.\n\n### The Alternative: Ishmael's Pluralism\n\nIshmael survives because he practices **multicultural vision** — looking at the whale through science, art, religion, humor, friendship, wonder, and fear, *without committing to any single lens*. He is the novel's model of sustainable consciousness.\n\nQueequeg's coffin — covered in unreadable Polynesian symbols — is the physical emblem of this argument. It saves Ishmael precisely because it contains knowledge he *can't decode*. Salvation comes from what you don't fully understand, not from what you've mastered.\n\n**Final thesis:**\n\n*Moby-Dick* argues that the greatest threat to human survival — psychological, political, ecological — is the refusal to see through more than one lens. The novel itself demonstrates the alternative: it's simultaneously a novel, a play, a sermon, a taxonomy, a philosophy treatise, and a comedy. It contains multitudes. That's not a flaw in its design — it's the entire argument.\n\nThe white whale is white because white contains all colors. The novel that tries to capture it must also contain all forms. And the reader who wants to understand it must be willing to see from every angle, knowing they'll never see everything.\n\nThat's the most important American novel ever written."
