    response: "The gap between Moby-Dick's cultural presence and its actual readership is probably the widest of any novel in English. Everyone knows \"Call me Ishmael\" and \"the white whale.\" Almost nobody knows what happens in between.\n\n**The cultural footprint:**\n\n**Language:** \"White whale\" has become a universal metaphor for an obsessive, possibly unattainable goal. \"My white whale\" is understood by people who've never read a page of Melville. This is actually a slight misreading — in the novel, the whale isn't unattainable, it's *destructive to pursue* — but the cultural usage has its own life.\n\n**Film and TV:** The 1956 John Huston film (with Gregory Peck as Ahab) cemented the visual iconography. Patrick Stewart played Ahab in a 1998 TV movie. Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan is a Moby-Dick retelling. Battlestar Galactica quotes it. Jaws is its descendant. Every story about an obsessive leader who pursues a great beast at any cost is, consciously or not, retelling Melville.\n\n**Music:** Led Zeppelin's \"Moby Dick\" (a drum solo). Mastodon's concept album *Leviathan*. Laurie Anderson's performance piece *Songs and Stories from Moby-Dick*.\n\n**Visual art:** Frank Stella's enormous Moby-Dick series (hundreds of pieces). Rockwell Kent's iconic 1930 illustrations.\n\n**Philosophy and theory:** The novel is cited in environmental philosophy, postcolonial studies, queer theory, disability studies, animal studies, and critical race theory. It's one of the most analyzed texts in any discipline.\n\n**The paradox:**\n\nMoby-Dick has become a *cultural meme* in the oldest sense — a replicating idea that travels independently of its source. The white whale symbolism, the \"Call me Ishmael\" opening, the image of a lone man fighting a great beast — these have propagated through culture far beyond the readership of the actual book.\n\nThis is either the greatest literary achievement (your work becomes part of the human symbolic vocabulary) or the greatest literary irony (your work is reduced to two catchphrases). Probably both. Melville would appreciate the contradiction."
